AUSTRALIAN BAT LYSSAVIRUS - AUSTRALIA (05): (QUEENSLAND) EQUINE, FATAL
**********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 19 May 2013
Source: The Telegraph, Australian Associated Press (AAP) report [edited]
http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/breaking-news/horse-centre-owner-opts-for-rabies-vaccine/story-fni0xqi3-1226646106578


Biosecurity officers are assessing all animals on a southwest Queensland property after a horse contracted the deadly bat-borne lyssavirus.

Tests have confirmed the 1st case of the rare virus in a horse, which was put down at an equestrian centre last Saturday [11 May 2013].

Another horse with similar signs was euthanized on the same property a fortnight ago, however Biosecurity Queensland says the horse was disposed of before it could be tested.

The centre's owner, Cameron Osborne, says his property and the area are not home to bat colonies. "We are in an area that's believed to be free of bats," Dr Osborne told AAP. "We don't have many trees on the property and we've taken care not to plant fruit trees or anything that attracts bats. No one knows if bats fly through here overnight but we certainly haven't seen them and my neighbours are of the same opinion. It's very puzzling."

Dr Osborne could not recall obvious bites or scratches on the 2 dead horses.

Biosecurity officers have quarantined the property and the animals on it, including 20 horses.

Up until now, the lyssavirus has only been known to infect humans from a bite or scratch from a bat.

All 3 people to have contracted the virus in Australia, all in Queensland, have died; 2 were in the late 1990s and the other was in February this year (2013).

Queensland Health is tracing people who came into contact with either of the 2 horses. Dr Osborne, former doctor for the Wallabies and Queensland rugby teams, and 3 other workers are undergoing precautionary treatment. He said others don't work on his property but came into contact with the sick horses at Highborne Farm, north of Warwick. Queensland Health was unable to confirm media reports 6 people are being treated.

"Because of possible exposure to the lyssavirus we've been advised it's very wise to have a rabies vaccination," Dr Osborne said.

"Worldwide, anyone who has been exposed to [lyssaviruses], who has not [yet] had any signs of the illness, and has followed through [with]the vaccination [series] has not developed the condition."

He said vaccination began on Saturday and they will require 3 more injections over a fortnight. "It's not nerve-racking but it is concerning," Dr Osborne said. "We are just following prudent biosecurity measures as we did when the horses began showing signs of being unwell."

He said a 3rd horse kept in the same paddock as the 2 sick horses had
not contracted the virus.

[Byline: Petrina Berry]

